    "question_id" : 10068099,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Given a <code>List&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, <code>add()</code> each song index <code>score</code> times, <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#shuffle%28java.util.List%29\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Collections.shuffle()</code></a> the list, and play in order. For better results, skip successive duplicates. More <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/2524394/230513\">here</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1370770,
      "reputation" : 13905,
      "user_id" : 1306033,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b2173914b52cdfca88c60aa3bb1bd43a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Michael Slade",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1306033/michael-slade"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1333981318,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495539868,
    "creation_date" : 1333981318,
    "answer_id" : 10074635,
    "question_id" : 10068099,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is no native support from any of the known databases for a random select.  IF you do some searches you might find something like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>select * from my_table order by rand();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But that is woefully inefficient as it attempts to sort the entire table.</p>\n\n<p>If your data set is not too big, you can simply pull the entire table into an array and select randomly from that array.</p>\n\n<p>Now wieghted selection, that is more tricky.</p>\n\n<p>A simpler version would work out something like this:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Get a list of all of the ids (<code>id)</code> and weights (<code>weight</code>) in the table.</li>\n<li>Iterate through the list and calculate the cumulative weight <code>cwieght</code> for each id.</li>\n<li>When you reach the end of the list you will have a total of all of the weights.  Select a random number <code>r</code> between 0 and that total.</li>\n<li>Scan through the list again and find the item where <code>r &gt;= cweight &amp;&amp; r &lt; cweight+weight</code>  You can use a binary chop search for this if you are game.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>There are <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6052603/fast-weighted-random-selection-from-very-large-set-of-values\">other</a> <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/352670/weighted-random-selection-with-and-without-replacement\">smarter approaches</a> to this as well, which depend on certain restrictions.</p>\n"
  } ],
